Text as data

Working with text

  • Text is an exceedingly complex form of data that is difficult to systematically analyze.
  • Two common concepts:
    • Regular expressions
    • Corpora

Regular expressions

Case study: Shakespeare

Project Gutenberg: www.gutenberg.org

Start simple

Begin by asking very fundamental questions:

  1. How long is this play?
  2. How many times does Macbeth speak?
  3. Who speaks the most?

1. How long is the play?

We should be able to get a decent approximation by pulling out any header and footer.

macbeth_inner <- macbeth %>%
  slice(271:3171)
dim(macbeth_inner)
## [1] 2901    1

Can this be improved?

grep()

  • Global regular expression print
  • R function and command-line tool
  • Needle in haystack paradigm
  • Patterns specified through regular expressions
grep(pattern = "MACBETH", x = unlist(macbeth), value = TRUE)

If value = FALSE (the default), it will return the indices of the matches instead of the values themselves.

Regex

A syntax to specify a general pattern of interest in text. Often used for searching for matches to the pattern in a text document. The pattern lives inside " " and is build up from general elements.

  • Character classes
  • Quantifiers and Alternation
  • Anchors

Character classes

  • . : any character except newline
grep("MAC.", macbeth, value = TRUE)[1:3]
## [1] "MACHINE READABLE COPIES MAY BE DISTRIBUTED SO LONG AS SUCH COPIES"
## [2] "MACHINE READABLE COPIES OF THIS ETEXT, SO LONG AS SUCH COPIES"    
## [3] "WITH PERMISSION.  ELECTRONIC AND MACHINE READABLE COPIES MAY BE"
grep("MACBETH\\.", macbeth, value = TRUE)[1:3]
## [1] "MACBETH. So foul and fair a day I have not seen."    
## [2] "MACBETH. Speak, if you can. What are you?"           
## [3] "MACBETH. Stay, you imperfect speakers, tell me more."

To escape a special character, you must use a backslash (or two in R).

Character classes

  • . : any character except newline
  • \w \d \s : word, digit, whitespace
(a <- macbeth[510])
## [1] "MACBETH. The Thane of Cawdor lives. Why do you dress me"
(a <- unlist(strsplit(a, "\\.")))
## [1] "MACBETH"                    " The Thane of Cawdor lives"
## [3] " Why do you dress me"
grep("\\s", a, value = TRUE)
## [1] " The Thane of Cawdor lives" " Why do you dress me"

Character classes

  • . any character except newline
  • \w \d \s : word, digit, whitespace
  • [abc] : any of a, b, or c
  • [^abc] : not a, b, or c
  • [a-g] : character between a and g

  • ^ : start of string
  • $ : end of string

Quantifiers and alternation

  • a*: 0 or more of a
  • a+ : 1 or more of a
  • a? : 0 or 1 of a
  • a{5} a{2,} : exactly five, two or more a
tail(grep("\\s{2,}", macbeth, value = TRUE))
## [1] "Brandish'd by man that's of a woman born.              Exit."     
## [2] "And more I beg not.                           Exit. Alarums."     
## [3] "Than terms can give thee out!                    They fight."     
## [4] "ALL. Hail, King of Scotland!                         Flourish."   
## [5] "WITH PERMISSION.  ELECTRONIC AND MACHINE READABLE COPIES MAY BE"  
## [6] "COMMERCIALLY.  PROHIBITED COMMERCIAL DISTRIBUTION INCLUDES BY ANY"

Quantifiers and alternation

  • a*: 0 or more of a
  • a+ : 1 or more of a
  • a? : 0 or 1 of a
  • a{5} a{2,} : exactly five, two or more a
  • ab|cd : match ab or cd

Quantifiers and alternation

grep("Thane of [F|G]", macbeth, value = TRUE)
## [1] "MACBETH, Thane of Glamis and Cawdor, a general in the King's"  
## [2] "MACDUFF, Thane of Fife, a nobleman of Scotland"                
## [3] "FIRST WITCH. All hail, Macbeth, hail to thee, Thane of Glamis!"

## [5] "Beware the Thane of Fife. Dismiss me. Enough."                 
## [6] "LADY MACBETH. The Thane of Fife had a wife; where is she now?"

Activity 8A

Write out the regex that will do the following:

  1. Identify first lines spoken by Lady Macbeth, Macbeth, or Macduff.
  2. Match everything in the left column and nothing in the right.

Activity 8

Using the babynames data,

  1. Find the top ten boys' names that end in a vowel.
  2. Create two top ten lists - one for boys and one for girls - for names ending with "joe", "jo", "Joe", or "Joe".
  3. Find the name/names that involve the greatest number of consecutive consonants.
